        "heading": "1.2 Expressing Concentration of Soiutions",
        "body": "<p>There are several methods by which we can describe the concentration of the solution quantitatively. Some of these are as follows Concentration Terms</p>\n<p>Mass Percentage (w/w %)</p>\n<p>Defmition</p>\n<p>The mass percentage of a component in a given solution is the mass of the</p>\n<p>Formula</p>\n<p>Examples</p>\n<p>Mass % of a component Mass of the component in the solution xlOO Total mass of the solution</p>\n<p>component per 100 g of the</p>\n<p>e.g. A 10% glucose in water by mass means that 10 g of glucose is dissolved in 90 g of water resulting in a 100 g of solution.</p>\n<p>solution.</p>\n<p>Volume Percentage</p>\n<p>The volume percentage is</p>\n<p>Volume % of a component</p>\n<p>(V/V%)</p>\n<p>the volume of the</p>\n<p>_ Volume of the component X 100</p>\n<p>component per 100 parts by volume of the solution.</p>\n<p>Mass by Volume</p>\n<p>It is the mass of solute</p>\n<p>Percentage (w/V %)</p>\n<p>dissolved in 100 mL of the solution.</p>\n<p>Total volume of solution</p>\n<p>Mass by volume % Mass of solute</p>\n<p>X 100</p>\n<p>Total volume of solution</p>\n<p>Parts Per Million</p>\n<p>It is defined as the number</p>\n<p>ppm</p>\n<p>(ppm)</p>\n<p>of parts of a component per million parts (10^) of the</p>\n<p>_ Number of parts of the component xlO^ Total number of parts of all components of the solution</p>\n<p>solution. It is used when a solute is</p>\n<p>present in trace quantities.</p>\n<p>e.g. 100mLof35%(V/V) solution of ethylene glycol contains 35 mL of ethylene glycol and 65 mL of water. e.g. A 10% solution of sodium chloride (w/V) means that 10 g of sodium chloride is dissolved in 100 mL of solution.</p>\n<p>e.g.(i) The concentration of pollutants in water or atmosphere is often expressed</p>\n<p>in terms of pg mL\"' or ppm. (ii) Gases like oxygen [weighs</p>\n<p>6x10\"^ g] dissolved in one litre of sea water is expressed</p>\n<p>in 5.8 g per lO^g or 5.8 ppm.</p>\n<p>Solutions</p>\n<p>Concentration</p>\n<p>Definition</p>\n<p>Terms</p>\n<p>Mole Fraction (5C)</p>\n<p>Formula</p>\n<p>It is the ratio of number of</p>\n<p>moles of one component to the total number of moles of</p>\n<p>all the components present in</p>\n<p>Examples</p>\n<p>Mole fraction of a component e.g. In a binary solution, if the Number of moles of the component number of moles of A and B are andtty, respectively, then Total number of moles of all mole fraction of A will be</p>\n<p>the components</p>\n<p>the solution.</p>\n<p>Similarly, mole fraction of B, n</p>\n<p>=1</p>\n<p>XB</p>\n<p>Molarity (M)</p>\n<p>It is defined as the number</p>\n<p>of moles of solute dissolved in one litre or one cubic</p>\n<p>Molarity =</p>\n<p>B</p>\n<p>Number of moles of solute</p>\n<p>e.g. 0.25 mol L\"' (or 0.25 M)</p>\n<p>Volume of solution (in litre)</p>\n<p>solution of NaOH means that</p>\n<p>0.25 moles (or 10 g) of NaOH</p>\n<p>decimetre of the solution.</p>\n<p>has been dissolved in one litre</p>\n<p>It is expressed in term of</p>\n<p>(or one cubic decimetre).</p>\n<p>mol L“'.</p>\n<p>Molality(m)</p>\n<p>It is defined as the number</p>\n<p>of moles of solute per kilogram (kg) of the solvent. It is expressed in term of mol kg\"'.</p>\n<p>Molality=</p>\n<p>Moles of solute</p>\n<p>e.g. 1.00 mol kg”' (or 1.00 m)</p>\n<p>Mass of solvent (in kg)</p>\n<p>solution of KCl means that</p>\n<p>1 mole (74.5 g) of KCl is dissolved in I kg of water.</p>\n<p>Note Mass %, ppm, mole fraction and molality are independent of temperature, whereas mass by volume %, volume % and molarity depends on temperature. This is because volume depends on temperature but mass does not.</p>",
        "keyFormulae": [
          "=1",
          "Molarity =",
          "Molality="
        ],
