        "heading": "2.1 Electrochemical Cells Redox Reactions",
        "body": "<p>generate electric current. Therefore, the redox reactions set up the basis of electrochemical cells and electrolytic cells which are</p>\n<p>&lt;&lt;&lt;SECTION 2.8 Fuel Cells&gt;&gt;&gt;</p>\n<p>discussed further. An electrochemical cell is a device in which</p>\n<p>&lt;&lt;&lt;SECTION 2.9 Corrosion&gt;&gt;&gt;</p>\n<p>chemical energy of the redox reaction is converted into electrical energy, while electrolytic cell do the reverse.</p>\n<p>&lt;&lt;&lt;SECTION 2.6 Electrolytic Cells and Electrolysis Working&gt;&gt;&gt;</p>\n<p>The two half-cell reactions in a Daniell cell are:</p>\n<p>■</p>\n<p>that the reaction continues to take place till the</p>\n<p>opposing voltage reaches the value of 1.1 V. Once it meets the value, the reaction stops</p>\n<p>altogether and no current or electrons flows through the cell. faxt=1-1V 'WWWWVWV</p>\n<p>T</p>\n<p>The zinc electrode may be called as the oxidation half-cell and the copper electrode as the reduction</p>\n<p>Zn(s) + Cu^^(aq)</p>\n<p>● We can construct innumerable number of galvanic cells on the pattern of Daniell cell by taking combinations of different half-cells.</p>\n<p>'—(J) /=0 Zn</p>\n<p>&gt; Zn^‘\"(flq)+Cu(s)</p>\n<p>CUSO4</p>\n<p>to the galvanic cell and increased slowly, we find</p>\n<p>&gt; Zn^*(aq) +2e\"(oxidation half-reaction) &gt; Cu(s) (reduction half-reaction) ● Cu^^(fl^)+2e“</p>\n<p>The overall redox reaction occurs as</p>\n<p>Cu</p>\n<p>Case II When the external potential is equal to I.IV. If an external opposite potential is applied</p>\n<p>● Zn(s)</p>\n<p>half-ceU.</p>\n<p>+ve</p>\n<p>1 ml ff</p>\n<p>—m</p>\n<p>ZnS04 \\</p>\n<p>Cathode</p>\n<p>Current</p>\n<p>-ve</p>\n<p>I ZnS04</p>\n<p>Cu</p>\n<p>CUSO4</p>\n<p>Electrochemistry</p>\n<p>Case III When the external potential is more than I.IV. The reactions get reversed and which also reverses the polarity of the electrodes. This cell is then called an electrolytic cell, a device for using electrical energy to carry out non-spontaneous chemical reactions. Hence, an electrochemical cell can behave like</p>\n<p>an electrolytic cell, when</p>\n<p>&gt; E cell-</p>\n<p>Now, electrons flow from Cu to Zn and current</p>\n<p>flows</p>\n<p>from</p>\n<p>Zn</p>\n<p>to</p>\n<p>Cu.</p>\n<p>Therefore,</p>\n<p>zinc</p>\n<p>is</p>\n<p>potential difference observed will be named as oxidation potential.</p>\n<p>a tendency to leave the electrolyte and deposit on the electrode making the electrode positively charged. Here, the metal undergoes reduction and the resulted potential difference will be named as reduction potential. «+</p>\n<p>+ne</p>\n<p>&gt; M</p>\n<p>The potential difference between the two half-cells is called the cell potential and is measured in volts.</p>\n<p>-vy/wwwwv e'</p>\n<p>Current</p>\n<p>+ve</p>\n<p>Zn</p>\n<p>M</p>\n<p>Cell Potential or EMF of a Cell</p>\n<p>^exl ^ ^</p>\n<p>Cathode</p>\n<p>&gt; M'\" +ne</p>\n<p>● On the other hand, metal ions in the solution have</p>\n<p>deposited at the zinc electrode and copper dissolves at copper electrode,</p>\n<p>&lt;s&gt;</p>\n<p>n+</p>\n<p>M</p>\n<p>Anode -ve</p>\n<p>II</p>\n<p>Cu</p>\n<p>In other words, the difference between standard</p>\n<p>reduction potential of cathode and standard reduction potential of anode is called ceU potential. po</p>\n<p>^ccll</p>\n<p>“ ^ cathode -E°anode — po</p>\n<p>It depends upon the following factors ZnS04</p>\n<p>CUSO4</p>\n<p>● Nature of metal and its ions</p>\n<p>● Concentrations of electrolytes used</p>\n<p>Salt-Bridge ● It is a U-shaped glass tube containing electrolytes (KCI, KNO3, NH4CI, etc.,) mixed in some kind of gel {like gelatine or agar-agar).</p>\n<p>● It plays an important role in working of an electrochemical cell as it completes the circuit and maintains the electrical neutrality</p>\n<p>of solutions in each of the respective half-cells. ● Salt-bridge prevents transference or diffusion of the solutions from</p>\n<p>one half cell to the other, it also prevents liquid-liquid junction-potential, i.e. the potential difference which arises between two solutions when in contact with each other.</p>\n<p>● Temperature</p>\n<p>Cell potential is also known as electromotive force (EMF) when no current flows through the cell.</p>\n<p>Cell Representation While representing the galvanic cell, the anode is written on the left and the cathode on the right.</p>\n<p>A vertical line (|) separates the metal from the metal ion (electrolyte solution) and a double vertical line (||) indicates a salt-bridge connecting the two half-cells (two electrolytes). The state of the metal and the solution is written with</p>\n<p>Some important Terms Related to Cell The various important terms related to cell are as follows Electrode Potential</p>\n<p>It refers to the potential difference developed between electrode and electrolyte in an electrochemical cell. Electrode potential may generate as a result of the following processes: ● Metal atoms of the electrode have a tendency to go into the solution as ions leaving behind the electrons at the electrode making it negatively charged. It means that the metal undergoes oxidation and the</p>\n<p>the concentration of the electrolyte in parenthesis,</p>\n<p>●^cell ” ■^righc (cathode)</p>\n<p>■^left (anode)</p>\n<p>Let us consider an example to understand the concept. Step I Write the cell reaction,</p>\n<p>Cu(s) -l- 2Ag'^ (aq)</p>\n<p>●&gt; Cu^’^(tjg)-I-2Ag(s)</p>\n<p>Step II Split the reaction into two half-cell reactions. At cathode (reduction)</p>\n<p>2Ag'^(a^) -h 2e~</p>\n<p>2Ag(s)</p>\n<p>At anode (oxidation)</p>\n<p>Cu(s)</p>\n<p>&gt; Cu^'^(aq)2e~</p>\n<p>Step III Represent the complete reaction according to the conversion discussed above.</p>\n<p>Cu(5)|Cu\"-^(ag)||Ag-^H)|Ag(s)</p>\n<p>■^ccll =^AgVAg “-^Cu^VCu General representation of an electrochemical cell is given as</p>\n<p>I M^\\aq) \\ M2(s) Anode Oxidation</p>\n<p>Reduction</p>\n<p>half-cell</p>\n<p>half-cell</p>\n<p>Cathode</p>\n<p>SHE consists of a platinum electrode coated with platinum black. The electrode is dipped in acidic solution of 1M ions and pure H 2 gas is bubbled through it at 1 bar pressure. The concentration of both the reduced and oxidised forms of hydrogen is maintained at unity. The SHE is represented as,</p>\n<p>Pt(5)|H2U)|H\"(^^q) Here, the reaction occurs as,</p>\n<p>Electrons flow this way</p>\n<p>^TEACHER’S TIP</p>\n<p>In case of electrochemical cell, remember LOAN word to avoid</p>\n<p>confusion about processes L Left, 0 Oxidation, A</p>\n<p>Anode, N</p>\n<p>This electrode has zero potential at all temperatures. The construction of the SHE is shown in the figure below.</p>\n<p>negative. 3— H2 ig) at 1 bar</p>",
