        "heading": "2.6 Electrolytic Cells and Electrolysis",
        "body": "<p>Electrolytic cells are those cells in which electrical energy is used to carry out non-spontaneous chemical reactions and the reactions taking place in an electrolytic cell is called electrolysis. In an electrolytic cell, external source of voltage is used to bring about a chemical reaction. One of the simplest electrolytic cell consists of two copper strips (which acts as anode and cathode) dipping in an aqueous solution of copper sulphate. The diagrammatic representation of the apparatus used in the process of electrolysis is shown in the figure given below. D.C. Source</p>\n<p>Ammeter</p>\n<p>e-</p>\n<p>e-</p>\n<p>Cathode</p>\n<p>m m</p>\n<p>Copper-</p>\n<p>Faraday’s Laws of Electrolysis The quantitative aspects of electrolysis was studied extensively by Michael Faraday and his laws of electrolysis are known as Faraday’s laws of electrolysis.</p>\n<p>1. Faraday’s First Law occurring at any electrode during electrolysis by passing current is directly proportional to the quantity of electricity passed through the electrolyte (in solution</p>\n<p>w</p>\n<p>or in molten state)”.</p>\n<p>m</p>\n<p>Thus, w g of the substance gets deposited on passing Q coulomb of electricity,</p>\n<p>'m</p>\n<p>sulphate</p>\n<p>Many metals, e.g., Na, Mg, Al etc., are produced on large scale by electrochemical reduction of their respective cations where no suitable chemical reducing agents are available for this purpose. Sodium (Na) and magnesium (Mg) metals are produced by the electrolysis of their fused chlorides. Aluminium (Al) is produced by the electrolysis of aluminium oxide in presence of cryolite.</p>\n<p>It states that “the amount of chemical reaction</p>\n<p>SAnode</p>\n<p>Application of Electrolytic Cells</p>\n<p>Now, let us discuss these laws as follows</p>\n<p>&lt;S)</p>\n<p>I-</p>\n<p>● The anode in an electrolytic cell is positive electrode where oxidation of anions (negative ions) occurs.</p>\n<p>m</p>\n<p>w oc Q or w = ZQ</p>\n<p>Working of Electrolytic Cells In an electrolytic cell, when a DC voltage is applied to the two electrodes, then copper is dissolved (oxidised) at anode and deposited (reduced) at cathode and following reactions take place.</p>\n<p>At cathode, Cu^'^(a^)+2e\" At anode,</p>\n<p>Cu(s)</p>\n<p>&gt; Cu (s)</p>\n<p>&gt; Cu^^(s) + 2e~</p>\n<p>In industrial process, impure copper rod is made as an anode that dissolves on passing current and pure copper</p>\n<p>rod is made cathode at which Cu^‘*‘ ions deposits. Thus, in an electrolytic cell, ● Cations (positive ions) are attracted towards the negative electrode, cathode and discharge by accepting electrons from the cathode. Hence,</p>\n<p>{■'Q = it)</p>\n<p>w -Zxit</p>\n<p>Electrolytic cell</p>\n<p>where, Q = quantity of electricity (in C), i = current (in A), t = time (ins), Z= constant of proportionality called electrochemical equivalent. It is defined as the amount of the substance deposited when lA of current is</p>\n<p>passed for Is (1C of charge is passed). Its unit is g C”L</p>\n<p>2. Faraday’s Second Law It states that “when the same quantity of electricity is passed through different electrolytes connected in series,</p>\n<p>the weight of different substances liberated at the electrodes are directly proportional to their equivalent weights. ^</p>\n<p>or</p>\n<p>Wi _ ^2 _ '^3 _</p>\n<p>w</p>\n<p>El</p>\n<p>En.</p>\n<p>E2</p>\n<p>£3</p>\n<p>Wi _ W2</p>\n<p>reduction occurs at cathode. (This is in contrast to</p>\n<p>where, w is the mass of substance and E is its</p>\n<p>galvanic cells, in which a cathode is a positive</p>\n<p>equivalent weight.</p>\n<p>electrode).</p>\n<p>^TEACHERS TIP</p>\n<p>Products of Electrolysis</p>\n<p>The equivalent mass (weight) of a substance deposited is equal to the atomic mass of an element divided by the number of electrons gained or lost by one atoni/ion of the element, i.e., Equivalent weight (£) =</p>\n<p>(i) Nature of material being electrolysed The products of electrolysis depend upon the standard electrode potentials of the material or electrodes. Also, the nature of electrolyte determines the process of electrolysis.</p>\n<p>Atomic mass</p>\n<p>No. of electrons gained or lost by one atom / ion Molar mass of element</p>\n<p>or,</p>\n<p>Valency</p>\n<p>Faraday’s Constant The amount of electricity (or charge) required for oxidation or reduction depends on the stoichiometry of the electrode reaction.</p>\n<p>&gt; Ag(s) One mole of the electron is required for the reduction -19</p>\n<p>The charge on an electron is 1.602x10 '^C. Therefore, the charge on one mole of electrons is = 96487 Cmol</p>\n<p>-19</p>\n<p>c</p>\n<p>-1</p>\n<p>This quantity of electricity is called Faraday’s constant and is represented by the symbol F. £</p>\n<p>W</p>\n<p>F</p>\n<p>Q</p>\n<p>Note Combining Faraday’s laws, we get, Z =—= —</p>",
