        "heading": "3.5 Integrated Rate Equations Rate Determining (Slow) Step",
        "body": "<p>Instantaneous rate is hard to measure, so the</p>\n<p>The slowest step of the reaction is considered as the rate determining step of the chemical reaction and it decides the overall rate of the reaction.</p>\n<p>Consider the following reaction, 2N2O5 4NO 2 D 2 The rate law for this equation is found to be, Rate of reaction = A: [N2O5] If the reaction occur by the collisions of two N 2O5 molecules as indicated by the balanced equation, it would be a second order reaction as</p>\n<p>Rate = k [N205]^But observed rate law suggests that it is a first order reaction which implies that the reaction is a complex reaction. So, it must take place in two steps in such a way that the slowest step should involve only one molecule of N2O5. Step I N2O5</p>\n<p>Slow</p>\n<p>SfepII N2O5 + NO3</p>\n<p>3NO 2</p>\n<p>differential rate equations is integrated to relate concentration of reactants or products with time. These equations are different for reactions of different orders. In this topic, we shall determine these equations only for zero and first order chemical reactions. Zero Order Reactions The reaction in which rate of the reaction is</p>\n<p>proportional to zero power of the concentration of reactants is called zero order reaction.</p>\n<p>Thus, in these reactions, the rate does not depend on the concentration of any of the reactants. Consider the reaction, R</p>\n<p>-&gt; P</p>\n<p>The differential rate equation can be written as Rate = -</p>\n<p>d[R] dt</p>\n<p>0</p>\n<p>= k[Rr =kxl</p>\n<p>d[R] = -kdt</p>\n<p>&gt; NO2 + NO3 Fast</p>\n<p>reactants as seen from the</p>\n<p>balanced equation.</p>\n<p>D2</p>\n<p>On integrating both sides, [R] = -kt+I</p>\n<p>...(0</p>\n<p>where, I is the constant of integration.</p>",
