              "prompt": "Why are most $\\text{Cu}^{2+}$ salts coloured but $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ salts colourless?",
              "steps": [
                "Cu²⁺ has 3d⁹ — one unpaired electron in the d-orbital.",
                "d–d transitions absorb visible light, hence colour.",
                "Zn²⁺ has 3d¹⁰ — fully filled, no d–d transitions, hence colourless."
              ],
              "finalAnswer": "Cu²⁺ has partially filled d (d–d transition → colour); Zn²⁺ is d¹⁰, no d–d transition → colourless.",
              "_source": "Authored from NCERT/ISC pattern"
