        "heading": "5.7 Bonding In Metal Carbonyls",
        "body": "<p>The homoleptic carbonyls, i.e., the compounds containing carbonyl ligands only, are formed by most of the transition metals. These carbonyls have simple and well defined structures.</p>\n<p>In these compounds, CO acts as a donor ligand and donates lone pairs of electrons of carbonyl carbon into vacant orbital of metal forming a-bond.</p>\n<p>It also behaves as an acceptor ligand and forms 7t-bond by back donation of electrons from filled d-orbital of</p>\n<p>● The pigment chlorophyll in plants, responsible for 2+ photosynthesis, is a coordination compound of Mg with porphyrin.</p>\n<p>● Vitamin Bj 2 also called cyanocobalamin, the anti-pernicious anaemia factor, is a coordination compound of cobalt. ● Enzymes like carboxypeptidase A and carbonic anhydrase (catalysts of biological systems) are also coordinated to metal ions.</p>\n<p>metal to vacant antibonding (jt* )-orbital of CO.</p>\n<p>In Medicinal Chemistry</p>\n<p>This back-bonding stabilises the metal-ligand interaction. It is also called synergic bonding.</p>\n<p>● The platinum complex ds-[Pt(NH3)2Cl2]&gt; commonly known as ds-platin, is used in the treatment of cancer. ● EDTA complex of calcium is used in the treatment of lead poisoning.</p>\n<p>Synergic bonding</p>\n<p>Structures of some representative homoleptic metal carbonyls are given below. CO CO</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>^Cr^</p>\n<p>OC</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>● Chelate therapy is widely used in medicinal chemistry. For example, the excess of copper and iron present in plant/animal system are removed by the chelating ligands D-penicillamine and desferrioxime B via the formation of complexes.</p>\n<p>I Fe—CO</p>\n<p>In Analytical Chemistry</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>Cr(CO)(i. Octahedral</p>\n<p>Fe(CO)5, Trigonal bipyramidal</p>\n<p>Coordination compounds are used in qualitative and quantitative chemical analysis. The familiar colour reactions given by metal ions with a number of ligands, as a result of</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>CO\"^l</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>OC</p>\n<p>o c</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>formation of coordination entities, form the basis for their</p>\n<p>CO</p>\n<p>detection and estimation by classical and instrumental methods of analysis. For example, EDTA, DMG, a-nitrosop-naphthoi, cupron, etc.</p>\n<p>OC ^Cd'^^^^Co^ CO OC</p>\n<p>o</p>\n<p>CojICOlg, Octacarbonyldicobalt(O) Structures of some representative homoleptic metal carbonyls</p>",
        "keyFormulae": [],
