              "id": "we_chem_6_T18_1",
              "prompt": "Why is chlorobenzene less reactive than chloromethane towards nucleophilic substitution?",
              "steps": [
                "In chlorobenzene, lone pair of Cl conjugates with the ring (resonance), giving partial double-bond character to C–Cl.",
                "C–Cl bond is shorter and stronger than in chloromethane.",
                "Also, sp² carbon is more electronegative and resists nucleophile attack."
              ],
              "finalAnswer": "Resonance gives C–Cl partial double-bond character → stronger bond, less reactive.",
              "_source": "Authored from NCERT/ISC pattern"
