        "heading": "6.5 Preparation of Haloarenes",
        "body": "<p>Bromo- and chloroarenes can be prepared by treating a freshly prepared diazonium salt solution with cuprous bromide or cuprous chloride.</p>\n<p>Haloarenes can be prepared by the following methods</p>\n<p>■NH2</p>\n<p>■N2X NaN02 -t- HX</p>\n<p>By Electrophilic Substitution of Aromatic Hydrocarbons</p>\n<p>273-278 K ^ Benzene diazonium</p>\n<p>Aryl chlorides and bromides can be easily prepared by</p>\n<p>halide</p>\n<p>electrophilic substitution of arenes with chlorine</p>\n<p>■N2X</p>\n<p>and bromine, respectively in dark, at ordinary temperature in the presence of a Lewis acid catalysts</p>\n<p>CU2X2</p>\n<p>such as iron or ferric halides or aluminium halides</p>\n<p>+ N2t Aiyl halide</p>\n<p>{FeCl3,FeBr3,AlCl3).</p>\n<p>(X'=Cl, Br)</p>\n<p>Lewis acid is used to generate the electrophile, i.e., Cl\"^</p>\n<p>and Br'*’ which reacts with aryl halide. Cl Fe/FeCl 310-320 K</p>\n<p>o + HC1 Chlorobenzene</p>\n<p>Replacement of the diazonium group by iodine is done simply by shaking the diazonium salt with potassium iodide.</p>\n<p>■N2X</p>\n<p>I KJ</p>\n<p>+ N2t</p>\n<p>Haloalkanes and Haloarenes</p>\n<p>Preparation of Haloarenes (At a glance)</p>\n<p>The Sandmeyer s reaction has been modified by using copper powder in place of cuprous halide. This reaction</p>\n<p>X</p>\n<p>is called Gattermann reaction.</p>\n<p>Njcr</p>\n<p>o</p>\n<p>+ x</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>Cu, HCl</p>\n<p>Fe</p>\n<p>+ HX</p>\n<p>2 (Dark)</p>\n<p>CU2C12/HC1</p>\n<p>&gt; O</p>\n<p>Cl + Njt</p>\n<p>Chlorobenzene</p>\n<p>Br + NjT</p>\n<p>Note If the diazonium group is replaced using fluoroboric acid, the reaction is called Balz-Schiemann reaction.</p>\n<p>N^cr</p>\n<p>N=NX-</p>\n<p>F</p>\n<p>n^zBf;</p>\n<p>I + N2t</p>\n<p>Benzene</p>\n<p>diazonium</p>\n<p>A^rOj+BF3+N2t + HCl</p>\n<p>OJ+HBF4 no Fluoroboric</p>\n<p>chloride</p>\n<p>(X=F. Cl. Br, I)</p>\n<p>Fluorobenzene</p>\n<p>acid</p>\n<p>F + BF3 + HCI + N2T</p>\n<p>Quick Test 2 1. Among the following alcohols, which will yield the corresponding alkyl chloride on reaction with concentrated HCl at room temperature?</p>\n<p>CH3</p>\n<p>CH3 —CH2 — CH—CH2OH , CH3CH2— C — OH, CH3</p>\n<p>CH3</p>\n<p>CH3 — CH2— CH2—CH—OH CH3</p>\n<p>2. Identify the products A and B formed in the following reaction.</p>\n<p>CH3—CH2—CH = CH—CH3+ HCl 3. Name the alkene which will yield</p>\n<p>A + B</p>\n<p>CH3</p>\n<p>5. Why aryl halides cannot be prepared by the reaction of phenol with HCl in the presence of ZnCl2? NCERT Exemplar 6. Write the structures and names of the compounds formed,</p>\n<p>when compound A with molecular formula CyHg, is treated NCERT Exemplar with CI2 in the presence of FeCl3. 7. How will you carry out the following conversions? (i) 2-bromopropane to 1-bromopropane CBSE2017 (ii) Benzene to p -chloronitrobenzene 8. Draw the structures of the major monohalo product for each of the following reactions. .CH2—CH3</p>\n<p>NCERT Exemplar</p>\n<p>1-chloro-l-methylcyclohexane by its reaction with HCl.</p>\n<p>Brj, Heat</p>\n<p>(i)</p>\n<p>Write the reactions involved.</p>\n<p>^ ?</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>4. Write the structure of the major organic products in each of the following reactions, (i) CH3CH2CH2Cl+ NaI</p>\n<p>NCERT</p>\n<p>(iv) CH3CH = CICHj) + HBr</p>\n<p>Acetone</p>\n<p>CH3</p>\n<p>Heat</p>\n<p>(ii) CH3CH2CH2OH + SOCI2 -</p>\n<p>pyridine 4</p>\n<p>(iii) CH3CH2CH</p>\n<p>Peroxide ^</p>\n<p>CH2 + HBr</p>\n<p>+ HBr</p>\n<p>(ii)</p>\n<p>■&gt;</p>\n<p>,OH Bfj. Heat</p>\n<p>(iii)</p>\n<p>HO—CH2</p>\n<p>For Solutions, See QR Code on Pg. 227</p>\n<p>^ ?</p>\n<p>? CBSE2017</p>",
