        "heading": "6.6 Physical Properties of Haloaikanes and Haloarenes",
        "body": "<p>Alkyl halides are colourless when they are pure. However, bromides and iodides develop colour when exposed to light.</p>\n<p>Some of the important physical properties of haloaikanes and haloarenes are as follows</p>\n<p>● For the same alkyl group, the boiling point of alkyl halides decreases in the order Rl &gt; RBr &gt; J?CI &gt; RP,</p>\n<p>because with increase in size and mass of halogen atom, the magnitude of van der Waals’ forces increases. ● For isomeric alkyl halides, boiling point decreases as the branching increases. This is because with increase in branching, the surface area of alkyl halide decreases and hence, the magnitude of the van der Waals’ forces of attraction decreases.</p>\n<p>(i) Physical state Methyl chloride, methyl bromide, ethyl chloride and some chlorofluoromethanes are gases at room</p>\n<p>CH3CH2CH2CH2Br&gt; (b.p.= 375 K)</p>\n<p>CH3</p>\n<p>temperature.</p>\n<p>Higher members are liquids or solids. Many volatile</p>\n<p>CH3CH2—CH — CH3 &gt;CH3—C—CH3</p>\n<p>halogen compounds have sweet smell. Haloarenes are generally colourless liquids or crystalline solids.</p>\n<p>(ii) Melting and Boiling points ● The boiling points of chlorides, bromides and iodides are higher than those of the hydrocarbons of comparable molecular mass. This is because molecules</p>\n<p>of organic halogen compounds are generally polar. Due to greater polarity and higher molecular mass as compared to the parent hydrocarbon, the</p>\n<p>intermolecular forces of attraction (dipole-dipole and van der Waals’) between molecules are stronger</p>\n<p>Br</p>\n<p>Br</p>\n<p>(b.p.= 364 K)</p>\n<p>(b.p. = 346 K)</p>\n<p>● Generally, the boiling points of chloro, bromo and iodo compounds increases as the number of halogen atom increases,</p>\n<p>e.g. CH3CI &lt; CH2CI2 &lt; CHCI3 &lt; CCI4 249 K</p>\n<p>313 K</p>\n<p>334 K</p>\n<p>350 K</p>\n<p>● Boiling points of isomeric dihalobenzenes are nearly the same. Cl</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>in the halogen derivatives.</p>\n<p>● As the molecular mass increases, the melting and</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>boiling points increases. This is because the attraction</p>\n<p>get stronger as the molecules get bigger in size and have more electrons.</p>\n<p>The pattern of variation of boiling points of different halides is depicted in table given below b.p. (K)</p>\n<p>□ Chlorides B Bromides □ Iodides</p>\n<p>m.p./K b.p./K</p>\n<p>Cl</p>\n<p>However, the p-lsomers have high melting point as compared to their o-and m-isomers. This is due to the</p>\n<p>symmetry of p-isomers that fits in the crystal lattice better as compared to o- and m-isomers.</p>\n<p>(ill) Density ● Fluoro and chloroalkanes are lighter than water, while bromo, iodo and polychloro derivatives are heavier than water.</p>\n<p>CH3CH2X CH3CH2CH2X Comparison of boiling points of some alkyl halides</p>\n<p>● With the increase in the number of C-atoms, halogen atoms and atomic mass of halogen atom, density increases.</p>\n<p>Haloalkanes and Haloarenes</p>\n<p>Nucleophilic Substitution of Alkyl Halides (R—X)</p>\n<p>(Iv) Solubility</p>\n<p>&gt;R—Nu+X\"</p>\n<p>R_X+ Nu</p>\n<p>● The solubility of haloalkanes in water is low. This is because the amount of energy released during the setup of new attractions between</p>\n<p>haloalkane</p>\n<p>and</p>\n<p>water</p>\n<p>molecules are not-sufficient to break the hydrogen bond between the water molecules.</p>\n<p>● They are soluble in organic solvents because the new intermolecular attractions between haloalkanes</p>\n<p>and</p>\n<p>Substitution</p>\n<p>Nucleophile (Nu\")</p>\n<p>Reagent</p>\n<p>product (R~Nu)</p>\n<p>Class of main</p>\n<p>product</p>\n<p>HO\"</p>\n<p>ROH</p>\n<p>Alcohol</p>\n<p>H2O</p>\n<p>H2O</p>\n<p>ROH</p>\n<p>Alcohol</p>\n<p>NaOR'</p>\n<p>R'O\"</p>\n<p>ROR</p>\n<p>Ether</p>\n<p>R—I</p>\n<p>Alkyl iodide</p>\n<p>NaOH(KOH)</p>\n<p>solvent molecules are of same strength as the ones being broken in the separate alkyl halide molecules and</p>\n<p>Nal</p>\n<p>r</p>\n<p>solvent molecules.</p>\n<p>NH3</p>\n<p>NH3</p>\n<p>RNH2</p>\n<p>Primary amine</p>\n<p>R’NH2</p>\n<p>R'NH2</p>\n<p>RNHR'</p>\n<p>sec-amine</p>\n<p>R’R\" NH</p>\n<p>R'R\" NH</p>\n<p>RNR’R\"</p>\n<p>tert-amine</p>\n<p>KCN</p>\n<p>C=N:</p>\n<p>RCN</p>\n<p>Nitrile (cyanide)</p>\n<p>RNC</p>\n<p>Isonitrile</p>",
