        "heading": "9.4 Preparation of Amines",
        "body": "<p>Raney Ni, Pt or Pd or chemically with active metals in</p>\n<p>Amines are prepared by the following methods.</p>\n<p>e.g. CH3NO2 +3H2</p>\n<p>acidic medium,</p>\n<p>Nitromethane</p>\n<p>By Reduction of Nitro Compounds Both aliphatic and aromatic primary amines can be prepared by the reduction of nitro compounds either catalytically with H 2 in the presence of finely divided</p>\n<p>C6H5NO2+3H2 Nitrobenzene</p>\n<p>Raney Ni/Pt Ethanol</p>\n<p>&gt; CH3NH2 +2H2O Methylamine</p>\n<p>H2 /Pd in ethanol or Sn + HCl or Fe + HCl</p>\n<p>C6H5NH2+2H2O Aniline</p>\n<p>Amines</p>\n<p>o</p>\n<p>Reduction with Fe scrap and HCl is preferred because FeCl 2 formed gets hydrolysed to release HCl during the reaction. Therefore, only a small amount of HCl is</p>\n<p>o</p>\n<p>N —H</p>\n<p>KOH(alc.)</p>\n<p>K. N K\"\"</p>\n<p>-HjO</p>\n<p>needed to initiate the reaction. O</p>\n<p>By Reduction of Nitriles Reduction of nitriles with lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH^) or catalytic hydrogenation produces primary amines. This method is used to prepare amines containing one carbon atom more than the starting amine. R—C=N</p>\n<p>Alkyl nitriles</p>\n<p>o</p>\n<p>.COONa^ NaOH(flq)</p>\n<p>N—i?</p>\n<p>R-NH2 *</p>\n<p>N1/H2</p>\n<p>&gt; R—CH2—NH2 LiAlH^ orNa(Hg)/C2H50H Alkyl amines</p>\n<p>By Reduction of Amides On reduction with LiAlH4, amides yield amines. O</p>\n<p>e.g.</p>\n<p>O</p>\n<p>Potassium phthalimide</p>\n<p>Phthalimide</p>\n<p>O</p>\n<p>N-alkylphthalimide</p>\n<p>This method produces only primary amines without the traces of secondary or tertiary amines. So, this method is preferred for the synthesis of primary amines.</p>\n<p>R—C—NH</p>\n<p>Alkyl amide</p>\n<p>CH3CONH Acetamide</p>\n<p>(i) UAIH4, ether</p>\n<p>&gt;R—CH2—NH2</p>\n<p>2 (i'i) H2O</p>\n<p>Alkyl amines</p>\n<p>(i) UAIH4, ether</p>\n<p>^ 00 H2O</p>\n<p>&gt; CH3CH2NH2 Ethylamine</p>\n<p>By Hofmann Bromamide Degradation Reaction This reaction is used for preparing amine containing one carbon less than the starting amide. This method was developed for the preparation of primary amines by reacting an amide with Br2 / Cl 2 in an aqueous or ethanolic solution of NaOH/KOH.</p>\n<p>In this reaction, migration of an alkyl or aryl group takes place from carbonyl carbon of the amide to the N-atom. o</p>\n<p>R—C—NH2+ Br2+4NaOH R</p>\n<p>NH2 +Na2C03 +2NaBr +2H2O</p>\n<p>e.g.CH3CH2 CONH2 + Br2 +4NaOH Amide</p>\n<p>CH3CH 2NH 2 + Na 2CO3 +2NaBr + 2H20 Amine</p>\n<p>^TEACHER'S TIP The above method is not useful for the preparation of aromatic primary amines because aryl halides do not undergo nucleophilic substitution with the anion formed by phthalimide.</p>\n<p>By Ammonolysis of Alkyl Halides This reaction is a nucleophilic substitution reaction carried out in a sealed tube at 373 K in which</p>\n<p>ammonia acting as a nucleophile, displaces the halogen atom. This process of cleavage of C X bond by ammonia is called ammonolysis.</p>\n<p>:nh3 + rXx Ammonia</p>\n<p>373 K</p>\n<p>Alkyl halide</p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p>-&gt; R</p>\n<p>Sealed tube</p>\n<p>NH,</p>\n<p>NH3X\";^</p>\n<p>RNH2</p>\n<p>Substituted</p>\n<p>1 “amine</p>\n<p>ammonium salt</p>\n<p>The primary amine thus obtained behaves as a nucleophile and on subsequent reaction with alkyl halide forms 2°, 3° amines and finally forms quaternary ammonium salt.</p>\n<p>RNH2</p>\n<p>R2NH</p>\n<p>R3N</p>\n<p>(n</p>\n<p>(2“)</p>\n<p>(3\")</p>\n<p>R4NX Quaternary ammonium salt</p>\n<p>By Gabriel Phthalimide Synthesis</p>\n<p>This method is not suitable for laboratory synthesis</p>\n<p>When a phthalimide is treated with ethanolic KOH, it</p>\n<p>amine salts and the quaternary ammonium salt which is often difficult to separate.</p>\n<p>forms potassium salt of phthalimide which on heating with alkyl halide followed by alkaline hydrolysis forms corresponding primary amines.</p>\n<p>because the mixture obtained consists of different</p>\n<p>On industrial scale, the mixture is separated by adding alkali to liberate free amines.</p>",
